item.title: Natalie add a quote by Samuel Beckett
item.description: "She felt, as she felt so often with Murphy, spattered with words that went dead as soon as they sounded; each word obliterated, before it had time to make sense, by the word that came next; so that in the end she did not know what had been said. It was like difficult music heard for the first time." -- Samuel Beckett

item.title: Natalie add a quote by Samuel Beckett
item.description: "I pause to record that I feel in extraordinary form. Delirium perhaps." -- Samuel Beckett

item.title: Natalie add a quote by Ernest Hemingway
item.description: "So far, about morals, I know only that what is moral is what you feel good after and what is immoral is what you feel bad after." -- Ernest Hemingway

item.title: Natalie add a quote by Bob Dylan
item.description: "I'll let you be in my dreams if I can be in yours" -- Bob Dylan

item.title: Natalie add a quote by Josef Albers
item.description: "As basic rules of a language must be practiced continually, and therefore are never fixed, so exercises toward distinct color effects never are done or over. New and different cases will be discovered time and again." -- Josef Albers

item.title: Natalie add a quote by Josef Albers
item.description: "I was for years in the yellow period, you know." -- Josef Albers

item.title: Natalie add a quote by Virginia Woolf
item.description: "and even a tea party means apprehension, breakage" -- Virginia Woolf

item.title: Natalie add a quote by Jean Cocteau
item.description: "It is excruciating to be an unbeliever with a spirit that is deeply religious." -- Jean Cocteau
